    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5bc006f3-95c4-4527-99ef-1421cc712681",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old Czech woman of medium build, with shoulder-length chestnut hair streaked with grey and a composed, somewhat weary expression. She works as a secondary school teacher of Czech literature in Brno, a role that keeps her on her feet for much of the day yet also involves long stretches of sitting while grading papers in the evenings. She lives with her husband and their teenage daughter in a flat in the Královo Pole district. In her free time she enjoys hiking in the Moravian hills with friends on weekends, tending her balcony garden, and reading contemporary fiction.\n\nOver the past several months {patientName} has been troubled by persistent, diffuse muscle pain described as a dull aching that on occasion turns into a pinching quality. The discomfort is most pronounced in the left shoulder girdle and left thigh, and is aggravated by sitting for prolonged periods when correcting homework in the evenings. She also notices generalised muscle stiffness in the morning that typically eases within 30 minutes. On palpation, the affected muscle groups are tender to touch. She does not report joint swelling, skin rash, or fever.\n\nIn recent weeks {patientName} has also begun to experience intermittent numbness and tingling in both hands, particularly after prolonged periods of grading papers, as well as occasional muscle twitching in her left thigh. She finds these new sensations unsettling and mentions they prompted her to seek medical review sooner than she otherwise might have. She does not report any weakness or loss of coordination.\n\n{patientName} is sociable and maintains a close circle of colleagues and hiking companions, yet the chronic pain has begun to limit her weekend activities and is affecting her mood. She sleeps poorly — waking repeatedly in the night because of the muscle discomfort — and admits to feeling more fatigued than usual. She does not smoke and drinks wine occasionally at social gatherings. She eats a balanced central-European diet but tends to avoid dairy since she dislikes the taste. Her general practitioner has carefully reviewed her current medications and noted that neither alendronate nor her levothyroxine dosing are considered the direct cause of her myalgia at this stage; a thorough workup has been undertaken to identify an idiopathic or rheumatological aetiology, including mildly elevated inflammatory markers and a weakly positive ANA, which together point toward a systemic or autoimmune underpinning requiring further monitoring."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4f1a18b0-cf15-4c5a-9d9f-d1dda922293a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a background of hypothyroidism diagnosed at age 43, managed with levothyroxine 75 mcg daily. Repeat thyroid function tests have confirmed that her TSH and free T4 are currently within the normal therapeutic range, making suboptimal thyroid hormone replacement an unlikely explanation for her ongoing muscle symptoms. She also has mild gastro-oesophageal reflux for which she takes omeprazole intermittently. She has borderline low bone density (dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry T-score −1.8 at the lumbar spine), documented two years ago; she was advised regarding calcium and vitamin D supplementation and was started on alendronate to prevent further bone loss. Her general practitioner reviewed the temporal relationship between alendronate initiation and onset of myalgia but concluded, after clinical assessment and the absence of the characteristic acute-phase reaction pattern, that alendronate is unlikely to be the primary driver of her chronic, progressive, diffuse muscle pain. The investigation focus has therefore shifted toward identifying an idiopathic inflammatory or early autoimmune aetiology.\n\nThis is not the first time {patientName} has experienced significant muscle pain; she recalls a milder but similar episode of diffuse muscle aching approximately five years ago, which resolved spontaneously over several weeks and was never formally investigated. She reports no prior hospitalisations and no surgical history. Her gynaecological history is unremarkable; she is perimenopausal. Blood tests for rheumatoid arthritis performed by her general practitioner earlier this year were within normal limits; however, inflammatory markers are mildly elevated and her ANA is weakly positive at 1:80 with a speckled pattern, warranting further rheumatological follow-up. She has a family history of lupus in her mother, osteoporosis in her maternal grandmother, and her maternal aunt has a longstanding history of chronic myalgia associated with fibromyalgia — providing a familial predisposition to musculoskeletal pain syndromes. {patientName} does not exercise regularly beyond recreational hiking and describes a sedentary evening routine. She denies alcohol misuse, illicit drug use, or tobacco use."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}